No free lunch theorem for security and utility in federated learning

Xiaojin Zhang xiaojinzhang@ust.hk Hong Kong University of Science and TechnologyClear Water BayHong Kong ,  Hanlin Gu allengu@webank.com WebankShenzhenChina ,  Lixin Fan lixinfan@webank.com WebankShenzhenChina ,  Kai Chen kaichen@cse.ust.hk Hong Kong University of Science and TechnologyClear Water BayHong Kong  and  Qiang Yang qyang@cse.ust.hk WeBank and Hong Kong University of Science and TechnologyHong Kong
(2022)
Abstract.

In a federated learning scenario where multiple parties jointly learn a model from their respective data, there exist two conflicting goals for the choice of appropriate algorithms. On one hand, private and sensitive training data must be kept secure as much as possible in the presence of semi-honest partners, while on the other hand, a certain amount of information has to be exchanged among different parties for the sake of learning utility. Such a challenge calls for the privacy-preserving federated learning solution, which maximizes the utility of the learned model and maintains a provable privacy guarantee of participating parties’ private data.

This article illustrates a general framework that a) formulates the trade-off between privacy loss and utility loss from a unified information-theoretic point of view, and b) delineates quantitative bounds of privacy-utility trade-off when different protection mechanisms including Randomization, Sparsity, and Homomorphic Encryption are used. It was shown that in general there is no free lunch for the privacy-utility trade-off and one has to trade the preserving of privacy with a certain degree of degraded utility. The quantitative analysis illustrated in this article may serve as the guidance for the design of practical federated learning algorithms.

1. Introduction

Modern machine learning techniques are data-hungry, and it is not uncommon to use trillion bytes of data in developing large pre-trained machine learning models, e.g., for natural language processing (Devlin et al., 2018; Dong et al., 2019) or image processing (Karras et al., 2019; Chen et al., 2021). For a large variety of machine learning applications, for instance, in social media or finance use cases, data are often distributed across multiple devices or institutions. Collecting such data onto a central server for training will incur additional communication overhead, management and business compliance costs, privacy issues, and even regulatory and judicial issues such as General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR)111GDPR is applicable as of May 25th, 2018 in all European member states to harmonize data privacy laws across Europe. https://gdpr.eu/. Federated Learning (FL) has been introduced as an effective technology to allow multiple parties to jointly train a model without gathering or exchanging private training data among different parties. Moreover, it is also required that information exchanged during the learning or inference stages do not disclose private data owned by respective parties to semi-honest adversaries (for a formal definition, see Sect. 2.2.1), who aim to espy or infer other parties’ private data from exchanged information. The requirements as such constitute the primary mandate for a novel statistical framework of privacy-preserving federated learning as illustrated in this article.

From an information theory point of view, the amount of information about private data that a semi-honest party can infer from exchanged information is inherently determined by the statistical dependency between private data and publicly exchanged information. Recent studies have shown that semi-honest adversaries can exploit this dependency to recover the private training images with pixel-level accuracy from exchanged gradients of learned models, e.g., by using Bayesian inference attacks (see Sect. 3.3 and (Zhu et al., 2019; Zhu and Han, 2020; He et al., 2019) for details). Taking such threat models into account, we therefore reiterate that a secure federated learning (SFL) scheme must a) support multiple parties to jointly train models and to make joint inferences without exchanging private data; b) have clearly defined threat models and security guarantees under these models.

In this article, we consider a horizontal federated learning (Yang et al., 2019a), or a cross-device federated learning (Kairouz et al., 2021) setting, in which multiple clients upload respective local models or model updates to an aggregator222We assume the existence of a centralized aggregator for the brevity of analysis. Yet the analysis is also applicable to the decentralized federated learning setting in which model aggregation is performed without an aggregator. Detailed discussion on this setting is out of the scope of this article though and will be reported elsewhere., who is responsible for aggregating multiple local models into a global model. There are a variety of application scenarios that use this scheme for federated learning (McMahan et al., 2016; McMahan et al., 2017; Yang et al., 2019b). The fundamental privacy-preserving requirement is to maintain potential privacy loss below an acceptable level. This is achieved by reducing the dependency between the exchanged model information and private data. The reduced dependency, however, makes the aggregated global model less accurate and leads to utility loss, such as a loss in model accuracy, as compared to a global model trained without using any protection. Severely degraded model utility indeed defeats the purpose of federated learning in the first place. We therefore propose in this article a unified statistical framework to analyze the privacy-utility trade-off on a rigorous theoretical foundation. The main results of our research are summarized as follows (also see Fig. 1 for a pictorial summary):

  • •

    First, we formulate the privacy leakage attack (Zhu et al., 2019; Zhu and Han, 2020; He et al., 2019) through a Bayesian inference attack perspective (Def. 1) (Geman and Geman, 1984a; Wasserman, 2004). A privacy metric called Bayesian Privacy is then proposed to quantify the additional amount of information about private data that a semi-honest adversary might gain by observing publicly exchanged information. Specifically, the information gain for adversaries i.e., Bayesian privacy leakage (Def. 2) is measured by distances between distributions of adversaries’ prior and posterior beliefs about private data. Also, an upper bound of Bayesian privacy leakage called ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-Bayesian Privacy provides the privacy-preserving guarantee regardless of any Bayesian inference attack that may be launched by semi-honest adversaries.

  • •

    Second, we put forth a statistical framework to cast the optimal privacy-utility trade-off as a constrained optimization problem in which the utility loss (Def. 3) is minimized subject to a preset upper bound of Bayesian privacy leakage (i.e. ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-Bayesian Privacy) constraint (see Sect. 4.2). A theoretical analysis of the trade-off is then manifested as Theorem 4.1, which dictates that a) a weighted sum of the privacy loss and utility loss is greater than a problem-dependent non-zero constant; b) relative weights between the privacy loss and utility loss depend on multiple factors including Bayesian inference attacks adversaries may launch, protection mechanisms adopted as well as distributions of the training and testing data. That is to say, in principle, one has to trade a decrease of the privacy-loss with a certain degree of increase of the utility loss, and vice versa333This principle bears an intriguing similarity to the no free lunch theorem for optimization and machine learning (Wolpert and Macready, 1997), which inspire us to name Theorem 4.1 “No free lunch theorem (NFL) for security and utility” in federated learning..

  • •

    Third, the general principle of Theorem 4.1 is applied to give quantitative analysis of the trade-off under specific privacy-protection mechanisms, including Randomization (Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020; Abadi et al., 2016), Sparsity (Shokri and Shmatikov, 2015; Gupta and Raskar, 2018; Thapa et al., 2020) and Homomorphic Encryption (HE) (Gentry, 2009; Zhang et al., 2020a) (see Theorem 4.2, 4.4 and 4.6). These theoretically justified results are of interest in their own rights. On the other hand, they are of pragmatic values in serving as a practical guidance to the design of federated learning algorithms under various scenarios (see Sect. 4.3 for applications).

To our best knowledge, the proposed Bayesian Privacy formulation is the first unified framework that explicitly considers both threat models (attacking mechanisms) and security models (protection mechanisms). It is also the first that is applicable to different privacy-protection mechanisms including randomization (Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020; Abadi et al., 2016), Sparsity (Shokri and Shmatikov, 2015; Gupta and Raskar, 2018; Thapa et al., 2020) and Homomorphic Encryption (Gentry, 2009; Zhang et al., 2020a). The rest of the article is organized as follows: Sect. 2 reviews existing works related to privacy measurements and federated learning; Sect. 3 illustrates the statistical framework based on Bayesian inference attacks and protection mechanisms; Sect. 4 illustrates the quantification of the privacy-utility trade-off (Theorem 4.1), the applications of the trade-off on different protection mechanisms are further presented in Sect. 4.3; The comparison of Bayesian Privacy with other privacy measurements is presented in Sect. 5. Finally, Sect. 6 concludes the article with discussions on future research plans.

2. Related Literature

This section gives a brief review of related work from distinct aspects, including privacy measurements, privacy attacking and protection methods in federated learning and privacy-utility trade-off.

2.1. Privacy Measurement

The need of privacy-persevering computing arises in various applications ranging from database mining, communication of secret information over public channels, and more recently, machine learning. Numerous definitions of privacy or privacy measurements proposed in the literature can be broadly categorized as follows as prior-independent and prior-dependent ones.

  • •

    Differential Privacy (DP) is a celebrated prior-independent definition proposed by Dwork et al. to protect individual privacy in response to queries about databases (Dwork et al., 2006; Dwork, 2006; Dwork et al., 2014). A series of DP variants were subsequently proposed to tighten the privacy budget under various conditions including Renyi Differential Privacy (RDP) with the natural relaxation of DP (Mironov, 2017), Gaussian Differential Privacy (GDP) with a closed-form privacy bound and stronger guarantee (Bu et al., 2020). Moreover, a large number of algorithms have been designed to achieve DP in federated learning (FL) (Seif et al., 2020; Truex et al., 2020) and Abadi et al. proposed the moments accountants of DP suitable for deep learning (Abadi et al., 2016). We refer readers to (Dwork, 2008; Ha et al., 2019) for a thorough coverage of privacy-preserving based on differential privacy. It is worth mentioning that DP-based measurements do not take into account the prior distributions of private data, i.e., DP and its variants are prior-independent except for Bayesian Differential Privacy (BDP) (Triastcyn and Faltings, 2020).

  • •

    Among different prior-dependent privacy measurements (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012; Asoodeh et al., 2018; Issa et al., 2019), Information Privacy (IP) (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012) is proposed to model the privacy leakage in terms of “amount of knowledge” learned by an adversary about the private data after observing the user’s output. The optimal privacy-utility trade-off is then cast, following the rate-distortion theory (Tretiak, 1974; Blau and Michaeli, 2019), as an optimization problem to minimize information leakage subject to utility loss constraints. The divergences adopted to quantify information leakages include KL divergence (mutual information) (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012), chi-squared divergence (Hsu et al., 2018), total variation divergence (Rassouli and Gündüz, 2019) and Renyi divergence (Liao et al., 2019).

2.2. Federated Learning

The notion of Federated Learning (FL) was initially proposed by McMahan et al. with the aim to build a machine learning model based on datasets that are distributed across multiple devices (McMahan et al., 2016; McMahan et al., 2017; Konečnỳ et al., 2016a, b). The main idea is to aggregate local models learned on multiple devices, yet, without sending private data to a semi-honest third-party server or other devices. Bearing in mind the privacy concern of secret data distributed across multiple institutions, Yang et al. extended applications of FL to a wide spectrum of use cases (Yang et al., 2019a) and classified FL scenarios into three categories:

  1. (1)

    horizontal federated learning: datasets share the same feature space but different space in samples;

  2. (2)

    vertical federated learning: two datasets share the same sample ID space but differ in feature space;

  3. (3)

    federated transfer learning: two datasets differ not only in samples but also in feature space.

Yang et al. (Yang et al., 2019a) also proposed the notion of secure federated learning to highlight the importance of protecting the privacy of training data from various kinds of adversary attacks. Horizontal and vertical federated learning are also referred to as cross-device and cross-silo federated learning, respectively, in (Kairouz et al., 2021). A wealth of literature as follows has been proposed to improve the privacy-preserving capability and model utility.

2.2.1. Threat model in Federated Learning

For the sake of privacy security, it is often necessary to consider the existence of semi-honest (honest-but-curious) adversaries in FL. The adversary is honest in the sense that he/she faithfully follows the collaborative learning protocol and does not submit any malformed message, but he/she may launch privacy attacks to espy the training data of other participants, by analyzing periodic updates to the joint model (e.g., gradients) during training. Such kind of attacks is referred to as Bayesian inference attack (please refer to 1), which can be broadly classified according to the information source exploited by a semi-honest adversary:

  • •

    Gradient inversion attack: Zhu et al. (Zhu et al., 2019; Zhu and Han, 2020) demonstrated that deep leakage attacks allow adversaries to restore the private data up to pixel-level accuracy from exchanged deep neural network model gradients. Following this seminal work, it was shown that adversaries can launch even more effective attacks by further exploiting various kinds of prior such as image smoothness prior by total variation loss (Geiping et al., 2020), image label prior (Zhao et al., 2020a), and group consistency of estimated images (Yin et al., 2021).

  • •

    Model Inversion attack from outputs: Split learning (Gupta and Raskar, 2018) allows a machine learning model to be separated and trained on multiple clients with low computing resources where each client only trains a small portion of the split models (e.g., a few layers of neural networks). However, adversaries could still infer private data from the model output in this case (Fredrikson et al., 2015; He et al., 2019). Gu et al. (Gu et al., 2021) later applied model inversion attack in a federated split learning (called splitfed) setting (Thapa et al., 2020) in which clients only upload partial information to the server.

  • •

    GAN-based attack: Generative Adversarial Network (GAN) networks were used to infer clients’ private data. Hitaj et al. (Hitaj et al., 2017) viewed the aggregate model as a discriminator of GAN to generate a distribution of specific classes. Wang et al. (Wang et al., 2019) proposed to learn a generator, which could recover user-specified private data in addition to the data distribution of a specific class.

2.2.2. Protection Mechanisms in Federated Learning

In order to protect private data from being disclosed by adversarial attacks, the following protection mechanisms have been adopted for secure federated learning444Note that the privacy analysis illustrated in Sect. 4.3 applies to Randomization, Sparsity and HE protection mechanisms and secret sharing.:

  • •

    Randomization: Differential privacy has been widely adopted to protect exchanged information in FL (Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020; Abadi et al., 2016) by adding to model information either Laplace noise or Gaussian noise (Dwork et al., 2006). Local differential privacy (Dwork, 2006) was also proposed to randomize response in federated learning (Truex et al., 2020; Seif et al., 2020; Zhao et al., 2020b). Despite its simplicity and popularity, the randomization approach inevitably leads to compromised performances in terms of slow convergence, low model utility, and loose privacy guarantee as documented in (Triastcyn and Faltings, 2020; Kim et al., 2021; Hu et al., 2015) etc.

  • •

    Encryption is a widely-adopted technique for protecting sensitive information. In particular, Homomorphic Encryption (HE) and its variants (Gentry, 2009; Rivest et al., 1978; Gentry, 2010) allows the aggregation of FL models to be performed directly on encrypted local models without decryption needed (Zhang et al., 2020b, 2019; Aono et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2019). However, extremely heavy computation and communication overhead incurred by HE prevent it from being readily applicable to large models such as deep neural networks with billions of model parameters. It remains an active research topic to come up with efficient HE algorithms to improve FL efficiency as demonstrated in (Aono et al., 2017; Zhang et al., 2020a).

  • •

    Sparsity based methods protect clients’ private data by hiding part of the information from being exchanged with other parties (Shokri and Shmatikov, 2015). In particular, Split Learning (SL) in a federated setting proposed to separate and hide part of neural network models from other parties (Gupta and Raskar, 2018) and splitfed (Thapa et al., 2020) combined SL and FL to improve the efficiency and utility at the same time.

  • •

    Secret Sharing (Shamir, 1979; Blakley, 1979; Bonawitz et al., 2017) were developed to distribute a secret among a group of participants. However, it requires extensive exchange of messages and entails a communication overhead not viable in many federated learning settings.

Some protection mechanism like (Li et al., 2020) does not belong to the field of federated learning, and is beyond the scope of our article.

2.3. Privacy-Utility Trade-Off

In the past decade, there has been wide interest in literature in understanding the privacy-utility trade-off:

  • •

    Some work focus on privacy-utility trade-off, where utility is quantified (inversely) via distortion (accuracy), and privacy via Information Privacy. Sankar et al. (Sankar et al., 2013) provided a precise quantification of the trade-off in databases between the privacy needs of the individuals and the utility of the published data. Makhdoumi et al. (Makhdoumi and Fawaz, 2013) modeled the privacy-utility trade-off according to the framework proposed by (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012). They regard the trade-off as a convex optimization problem, which aims at minimizing the mutual information between the private data and released data under the constraint of utility (distortion) of released data. Moreover, Rassouli et al. (Rassouli and Gündüz, 2019) further defined the privacy using total variation distance and illustrated that the optimal privacy-utility trade-off could be solved using a standard linear program. Also, Wang et al. (Wang and Calmon, 2017) provided a trade-off when utility and privacy were both evaluated using χ2superscript𝜒2\chi^{2}-based information measures.

  • •

    The trade-off of utility with relaxed privacy-preserving capability was considered necessary by Dwork et. al. for queries to be useful (Dwork and Naor, 2010) and she also gave an quantitative analysis that relates (ϵ,0)italic-ϵ0(\epsilon,0)-DP with the maximal error (in utility) bounded by Ω​(1ϵ)Ω1italic-ϵ\Omega(\frac{1}{\epsilon}) (Dwork et al., 2014). Differential privacy budget ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon of privacy-preserving algorithms was later related to the convergence (utility) of privacy-preserving algorithms (Wang et al., 2017; Girgis et al., 2021).

To sum up, in existing work we witnessed a compelling need to lay down a solid foundation for the design of novel federated learning algorithms. Especially, the recent Bayesian inference type of threats (Zhu et al., 2019; Zhu and Han, 2020; Geiping et al., 2020; Zhao et al., 2020a; Yin et al., 2021) were not explicitly modeled by existing privacy definitions, e.g., Differential Privacy which is considered the gold standard definition of privacy. This shortage of rigorous formulations makes it unclear for practitioners how to determine the optimal choice of algorithm design concerning the privacy-utility trade-off. There are no existing frameworks that simultaneously take into account different protection mechanisms, including randomization and Homomorphic Encryption. The rest of the present article therefore will illustrate such a novel statistical framework based on Bayesian inference attack which aims to address aforementioned issues not properly resolved in existing work.

3.2. General Setup

In this work, we consider a horizontal federated learning scenario, or cross-device federated learning (Kairouz et al., 2021), where multiple (K𝐾K) participants555In this article we use participant, party, client interchangeably to refer to a device or institute that participates in the federated learning. collaboratively learn a global model without exposing their private training data (McMahan et al., 2017; Yang et al., 2019a). The requirement of adopting certain protection of private data is due to the threat model. Some semi-honest adversaries may launch privacy attacks on exchanged information to infer private data of other participants (for a formal definition of semi-honest adversaries, see Sect. 2.2.1). Initially, the server distributes the global model information to all the clients. The overall secure federated learning (SFL) procedures are illustrated in the left panel of Fig. 2 and summarized as follows:

  1. With the global model information from the server, each client k𝑘k trains the local model using his/her own data set Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k}, and obtains the local model information Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}, which follows a distribution Pk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑃𝑘𝒪P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}. The objective of learning Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} is to maximize the model utility Uksubscript𝑈𝑘U_{k}.

  2. In order to prevent semi-honest adversaries from inferring other clients’ private information Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} according to Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}, the client adopts a protection mechanism M𝑀M to convert model information Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} to protected model information Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}.

  3. Each client uploads the protected information Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} to the server and aggregates as a new global model Wa𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑎𝒮W_{a}^{\mathcal{S}}.

  4. The clients download the global model Wa𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑎𝒮W_{a}^{\mathcal{S}} and continue to update the local model information.

The processes ①-④ iterate until the utility of the aggregated model does not improve.
Remark: In SFL, the local model information includes the model parameters, model gradients and model outputs, all of which may optionally be exchanged to the aggregator and get exposed to semi-honest adversaries (see details in the Appendix B). The goal of the protection mechanism M𝑀M is to protect private data such that the dependency between Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} and Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} is reduced, as compared to the dependency between the unprotected information Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} and Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k}.

In this SFL setting, the privacy loss and utility loss as illustrated in right panel of Fig. 2 are considered:

  1. (1)

    For the sake of privacy-preserving, a Bayesian privacy leakage measure (see Def. 2) is used to quantify the amount of information about private data that semi-honest adversaries may still infer in spite of the protection mechanisms applied to publicly exposed information. The Bayesian privacy leakage allows one to evaluate the security of a secure federated learning scheme and justifies that the adopted protection mechanism is secure in thwarting Bayesian inference attacks if the Bayesian privacy leakage is less than an acceptable threshold (see Sect. 4.2).

  2. (2)

    The protection mechanism modifies the original model information Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} to its protected counterpart Wk𝒮subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒮𝑘W^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}, and induces the local model to behave less accurately. Consequently, the aggregated global model is less accurate and the incurred utility loss is defined as the difference of utilities with and without protections (Def. 3).

3.3. Bayesian Inference Attack in Secure Federated Learning

It was shown that semi-honest adversaries could recover private training images up to pixel-level accuracy from unprotected gradients of learned models, e.g., by using efficient Bayesian inference attacks ((Zhu and Han, 2020; He et al., 2019)). The former one aims to find Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} to best match Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} (maximize the likelihood of Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}) and the latter one aims to make the prior of Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} more significant. In short, Bayesian inference attack establishes the posterior belief of Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} conditioned on Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}, denoted as fDk|Wk𝒮subscript𝑓conditionalsubscript𝐷𝑘superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮f_{D_{k}|W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}}.

The learned conditional distribution fDk|Wk𝒮subscript𝑓conditionalsubscript𝐷𝑘superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮f_{D_{k}|W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}} from the Bayesian inference attack reflects the dependency between Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} and Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k}, which determines the amount of information that adversaries may infer about Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} after observing Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}. In case the exposed information Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} is independent of the private data Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k}, then the posterior belief fDk|Wk𝒮subscript𝑓conditionalsubscript𝐷𝑘superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮f_{D_{k}|W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}} is guaranteed to be indistinguishable from the prior fDksubscript𝑓subscript𝐷𝑘f_{D_{k}} and the Bayesian privacy leakage is zero. This extreme case corresponds to the Semantic Security (SS) in cryptosystems (Goldwasser and Micali, 1984).

Remark:
(1) Bayesian inference attack defined here is a concrete realization of the semi-honest participant assumption. The attacker learns information from other parties and attempts to infer the private information held by other parties. The attacker does not actively inject information on exchanged messages in order to gain more private information or “poison” the joint model, however.

(2) It is required that the time cost of the Bayesian inference attack is polynomial. Given this requirement, adversaries cannot gain any additional information about the private data of clients if the attacking cost increases exponentially, e.g., against Homomorphic Encryption (Gentry, 2009). From a practical point of view, we give in Appendix B.4 detailed analysis of Bayesian inference attack including gradient inversion attack, model inversion attack and brute-force attack against different protection mechanisms.

(3) We formulate three attacks including gradient-inverse attack (Zhu and Han, 2020; Geiping et al., 2020; Zhao et al., 2020a; Yin et al., 2021), model inversion attack (Fredrikson et al., 2015; He et al., 2019) and brute-force attack (especially for encryption) from the Bayesian inference perspective (see details in Appendix B). These attacking approaches differ in the types of exposed information, including model, model gradients and model outputs in SFL. Moreover, the prior (denoted as Fkℬsubscriptsuperscript𝐹ℬ𝑘F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k}) is an important factor for inferring the private data. For example, if the attacker knows the label of an image is “cat”, he/she may use an averaged “cat” image to initialize the restored image and significantly improve the accuracy of restored data (the influence of prior for the attack is shown in Appendix B.1.1).

The Bayesian privacy leakage measures the discrepancy between the adversaries’ belief with and without leaked information. Moreover, the Bayesian privacy leakage is averaged with respect to the protected model information variable which is exposed to adversaries.

4. A general framework for the Privacy-Utility Trade-Off

In Sect. 3, we have introduced the definition of privacy leakage and utility loss in SFL. In this section, we first lay down the rigorous analysis of the trade-off between Bayesian privacy leakage and utility loss (no free lunch theorem). Then we formulate the privacy-utility trade-off as an optimization problem, which minimizes the utility loss under the ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-Bayesian privacy constraint. Finally, we apply the proposed no free lunch theorem between Bayesian privacy leakage and utility loss into four protection mechanisms in SFL.

4.1. Theoretical Analysis for Privacy-Utility Trade-Off

The idea of privacy-preserving is to modify the unprotected information and guarantee that the private data cannot be disclosed to semi-honest adversaries. In order to protect privacy, the protected information denoted as Wk𝒮subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒮𝑘W^{\mathcal{S}}_{k} is shared. The utility loss quantifies the increase of expected average loss incurred by the released information Wk𝒮subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒮𝑘W^{\mathcal{S}}_{k} compared with the utility caused by Wk𝒪subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒪𝑘W^{\mathcal{O}}_{k}. Note that Wk𝒮subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒮𝑘W^{\mathcal{S}}_{k} and Wk𝒪subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒪𝑘W^{\mathcal{O}}_{k} respectively follow distributions Pk𝒮subscriptsuperscript𝑃𝒮𝑘P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k} and Pk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑃𝑘𝒪P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}. In this setting, we want to characterize the limitation of privacy-preserving mechanisms. It requires to measure the amount of utility that is inevitable to lose in order to protect privacy. Intuitively, the larger the change exerted on Wk𝒪subscriptsuperscript𝑊𝒪𝑘W^{\mathcal{O}}_{k} is, the more secure the privacy protection is, and meanwhile, the less accurate the output is. We first measure the extent of modification using the total variation distance between the unprotected distribution and the protected distribution. Then, we use this distance as a key element for connecting the privacy leakage and the utility loss. Note that the union of 𝒲k𝒮superscriptsubscript𝒲𝑘𝒮\mathcal{W}_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} (the support of Pk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑃𝑘𝒮P_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}) and 𝒲k𝒪superscriptsubscript𝒲𝑘𝒪\mathcal{W}_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} (the support of Pk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑃𝑘𝒪P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}) is denoted as 𝒲ksubscript𝒲𝑘\mathcal{W}_{k}.

Definition 4.0 (Optimal parameters).

Let 𝒲a∗subscriptsuperscript𝒲𝑎\mathcal{W}^{*}_{a} represent the set of parameters achieving the maximum utility. Specifically,

The following theorem represents the central result of this work. As a form of the No Free Lunch (NFL) theorem, it states that privacy-protection and utility enhancement of a joint model in our semi-honest SFL setting is bounded by a constant. If one increases privacy protection, one risks losing some utility of the joint model, and vice versa.

Theorem 4.1 illustrates that the summation of the average privacy leakage of the clients and the utility loss is lower bounded by a problem-dependent constant. As shown in Fig. 3, Eq. (6) is based on the triangle inequality of the Jensen-Shannon measure adopted in Bayesian privacy leakage 4.1. It essentially dedicates that one has to trade a decrease of the privacy leakage (ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p}) with a certain degree of the increase of the utility loss (ϵusubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑢\epsilon_{u}) and vice versa. This principle bears an intriguing similarity to the no free lunch theorem for optimization and machine learning (Wolpert and Macready, 1997), which dedicated that “if an algorithm performs well on a certain class of problems then it necessarily pays for that with degraded performance on the set of all remaining problems”. We therefore name Eq. (6) “no free lunch theorem (NFL) for security and utility” in federated learning.

Remark: TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}) in Eq. (5) provides an upper bound of the modification brought by the protection mechanism, in terms of the distance between distributions of model information with and without protection methods being applied.

4.2. Privacy-Preserving Optimization

In the privacy-preserving machine learning scenario, clients aim to maintain maximal possible model utility without disclosing private information beyond an acceptable level. We can view this trade-off as an optimization problem. The goal is to minimize the utility loss subject to the privacy-preserving constraint. Let the Bayesian privacy leakage ϵpsubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝\epsilon_{p} be defined as Def. 2, we say a SFL system guarantees ϵitalic-ϵ\mathbf{\epsilon}-Bayesian Privacy if it holds that

(7) ϵp≤ϵ.subscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝italic-ϵ\epsilon_{p}\leq\epsilon.

ϵitalic-ϵ{\epsilon}-Bayesian Privacy guarantees that the Bayesian privacy leakage of the SFL system never exceeds a prescribed threshold ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon as the security requirement. For a federated machine learning system, the goal is to find a protection mechanism M𝑀M that achieves the minimum aggregated utility loss. These two requirements can be cast as a constrained optimization problem over the protection mechanism:

(10) minMϵu:=1K​∑k=1K[Uk​(Pa𝒪)−Uk​(Pa𝒮)],subject toϵp=1K​∑k=1KJS(Fk𝒜||Fkℬ)≤ϵ.\displaystyle\begin{array}[]{r@{\quad}l@{}l@{\quad}l}\quad\min\limits_{M}&\epsilon_{u}:=\frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^{K}[U_{k}(P_{a}^{\mathcal{O}})-U_{k}(P_{a}^{\mathcal{S}})],\\ \text{subject to}&\epsilon_{p}=\frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^{K}\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})}\leq\epsilon.\\ \end{array}

Remark:

(1) The constant ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon imposed in Eq. (10) provides a privacy security guarantee that one can achieve, regardless of a variety of Bayesian inference attacks that may be launched by adversaries.

(2) This constrained optimization problem is closely related to the optimization formulated (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012) which instead aims to minimize the information leakage while the utility loss is guaranteed to be less than a given threshold.

4.3. Applications of Privacy-Utility Trade-off

In this section, we apply the no free lunch theorem between the Bayesian privacy leakage and utility loss on four privacy-preserving mechanisms: Randomization (Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020; Abadi et al., 2016), Sparsity (Shokri and Shmatikov, 2015; Gupta and Raskar, 2018; Thapa et al., 2020), Homomorphic Encryption (Gentry, 2009; Zhang et al., 2020a) and Secret Sharing (Shamir, 1979; Blakley, 1979; Bonawitz et al., 2017)999secure hardware(Liu et al., 2022) was used in federated learning but we don’t include it in our analysis since it requires to send private data to a trustworthy third-part which violates the semi-honest adversaries setting considered in this article.. We analyze the influence of specific protection mechanisms’ parameters on the fluctuation of privacy leakage and utility loss.

4.3.1. Randomization Mechanism

Randomization mechanism is a natural choice since its noise parameter e.g., σ𝜎\sigma allows a flexible control of the trade-off. In SFL, one of the Randomization methods is to add random noise such as Gaussian noise to model gradients (Abadi et al., 2016; Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020). 4.3.3. Homomorphic Encryption

Homomorphic Encryption (HE) (Gentry, 2009; Rivest et al., 1978; Gentry, 2010) allows certain computation (e.g., addition) to be performed directly on ciphertexts, without decrypting them first. Such characteristic allows applying HE into FL to protect privacy because the server only accesses the uploaded parameters of users on ciphertexts instead of clients’ plaintext directly (Zhang et al., 2020b, 2019; Aono et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2019). Specifically, in federated learning, the uploaded model weights or gradients have been encrypted by the clients themselves. Therefore, it is hard for adversaries to espy the exposed information and infer clients’ private data. The following theorem evaluates the privacy leakage and utility loss of the approximate eigenvector method (Gentry et al., 2013), which is a widely-used method of HE.

5. Discussion

The section illustrates the comparison of the proposed Bayesian Privacy with respect to Differential Privacy (Dwork et al., 2014), Bayesian Differential Privacy BDP (Triastcyn and Faltings, 2020), Local Differential Privacy (Duchi et al., 2013) and Information Privacy (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012). A brief summary of the comparison is summarized in Table 2.

5.1. The comparison with Differential Privacy and its variants

We illustrate the comparison of Bayesian Privacy with respect to Differential Privacy and its variants as follows.

  • •

    First, the privacy-utility trade-off analyzed in differential privacy (DP) is essentially characterized by a reciprocal relation as shown by Theorem 8.7 of (Dwork et al., 2014), which dedicates that the outputs protected by an ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon-differentially private mechanism have the maximum error Ω​(1ϵ)Ω1italic-ϵ\Omega\left(\frac{1}{\epsilon}\right). This trade-off analysis is in contrast to the No free lunch theorem (Theorem 4.1) in the present article, which dictates that the sum of privacy loss and utility loss is greater than a problem-dependent constant.

  • •

    Second, it is shown that a ξ𝜉\xi-maximum Bayesian privacy preserving mapping fW|S​(⋅)subscript𝑓conditional𝑊𝑆⋅f_{W|S}(\cdot) is (2​ξ)2𝜉(2\xi)-differentially private (see Appendix D for details).

  • •

    Third, the privacy-utility trade-off established by the local differential privacy dedicates that, for an α𝛼\alpha-private estimator, its minimax error bound (in utility) is greater than a constant that is proportional to 1α21superscript𝛼2\frac{1}{\alpha^{2}} (see Theorem 1 in (Duchi et al., 2013)).

  • •

    Fourth, Bayesian Differential Privacy (BDP) was also proposed to measure the privacy loss following Bayesian rule (Duchi et al., 2013). Nevertheless, BDP estimated the posterior of query outputs (denoted by S𝑆S) given private data (denoted by x𝑥x). This is in sharp contrast to the proposed Bayesian Privacy, which models adversaries’ posterior belief of private data (denoted by S𝑆S) given publicly exchanged information (denoted by W𝒮superscript𝑊𝒮W^{\mathcal{S}}). Moreover, no privacy-utility trade-off analysis was provided for BDP in (Duchi et al., 2013).

  • •

    Last but not least, DP and its variants are not amenable to include encryption as a protection mechanism. To our best knowledge, the SFL framework based on Bayesian inference attack is the first that is applicable to different privacy-protection mechanisms, including randomization in Differential Privacy (Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020; Abadi et al., 2016), Sparsity (Shokri and Shmatikov, 2015; Gupta and Raskar, 2018; Thapa et al., 2020), Homomorphic Encryption (Gentry, 2009; Zhang et al., 2020a) and Secret Sharing (Shamir, 1979; Blakley, 1979; Bonawitz et al., 2017).

5.2. The relationship between Bayesian Privacy and Information Privacy

There are three fundamental differences between Bayesian Privacy (BP) and Information Privacy (IP) (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012) as shown below.

  • •

    One fundamental difference between BP and IP lies in the fact that BP is formulated within a secure federated learning setting as illustrated in Sect. 3, while it is unclear how to apply IP for delineating the privacy-utility trade-off in distributed learning scenarios.

  • •

    As per the privacy definitions, BP involves the averaged gain of information about private data that an adversary may obtain by observing publicly exposed model information (see Def. 2 in this article). On the other hand, information privacy is defined based on the bound of such information gain (see Def. 6 in (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012)). Note that we also give the bounds of Bayesian Privacy in Eq. (7), which is nevertheless based on the average gain.

  • •

    In terms of the privacy-utility trade-off, the optimal trade-off in BP is cast as the solution of a constrained optimization where the goal is to minimize utility loss subject to the hard constrain of maintaining Bayesian privacy leakage less than an acceptable threshold (the problem in Eq. (10)). In contrast, the optimal trade-off in IP is to minimize the privacy leakage subject to a given utility loss constrain (Def. 3 in (du Pin Calmon and Fawaz, 2012)).

Remark: It is worth noting that the Bayesian privacy is measured using JS divergence instead of KL divergence. Unlike KL divergence, JS divergence is symmetrical and its square root satisfies the triangle inequality. The property of triangular inequality of JS divergence facilitates the derivation of our main results illustrated in Sect. 4.1.

6. Conclusion

In this article, we proposed a statistical framework in SFL based on Bayesian inference attack to take into account two compelling requirements i.e. the protection of private data as well as the maximization of model utility in secure federated learning (SFL). The proposed framework is based on the cornerstone definition of Bayesian privacy Leakage that quantitatively measures the amount of information about private data that semi-honest adversaries may infer from the espied information during the SFL learning process. Then the trade-off privacy and utility is formulated as an optimization problem in which the goal is to find a modified distribution of exchanged model information that achieves the smallest utility loss without incurring privacy loss above an acceptable level. The theoretical analysis of the trade-off then leads us to the No Free Lunch (NFL) theorem for federated learning, which dictates that one has to trade a high privacy persevering guarantee with a certain degree of utility loss, and vice versa. This trade-off analysis is applicable to protection mechanisms including Randomization (Geyer et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2020; Abadi et al., 2016) Sparsity (Shokri and Shmatikov, 2015; Gupta and Raskar, 2018; Thapa et al., 2020), Homomorphic Encryption (Gentry, 2009; Zhang et al., 2020a) and Secret Sharing (Shamir, 1979; Blakley, 1979; Bonawitz et al., 2017) which are special cases of the general theorem proved in Theorem 4.1.

The analysis of privacy-utility trade-off in secure federated learning (SFL), to our best knowledge, is the first work that takes into account different specific protection mechanisms, including DP and HE, in a unified framework. While the main result disclosed in this article is inspiring, we plan to apply the technique we developed during this research endeavor to explore in the future the trade-off between efficiency and privacy, which provides a more comprehensive view of secure federated learning.

Lemma A.2.

Let ϵp,ksubscriptitalic-ϵ𝑝𝑘\epsilon_{p,k} be defined in Definition 2. Let Pk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑃𝑘𝒪P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} and Pk𝒮subscriptsuperscript𝑃𝒮𝑘P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k} represent the distribution of the parameter of client k𝑘k before and after being protected. Let Fkℬsubscriptsuperscript𝐹ℬ𝑘F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k} and Fk𝒜subscriptsuperscript𝐹𝒜𝑘F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k} represent the belief of client k𝑘k about D𝐷D before and after observing the released parameter. Then we have

(22) JS(Fk𝒪||Fkℬ)≤ϵp,k+12(e2​ξ−1)TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮).\displaystyle\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})}\leq\epsilon_{p,k}+\frac{1}{2}(e^{2\xi}-1){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}).

Consequently, we have

1K∑k=1KJS(Fk𝒪||Fkℬ)≤ϵp+1K∑k=1K12(e2​ξ−1)TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮).\displaystyle\frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^{K}\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})}\leq\epsilon_{p}+\frac{1}{K}\sum_{k=1}^{K}\frac{1}{2}(e^{2\xi}-1){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}).
Proof.

From Lemma A.1, we know that

JS(Fk𝒜||Fk𝒪)≤14(e2​ξ−1)2TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮)2.\displaystyle{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k})\leq\frac{1}{4}(e^{2\xi}-1)^{2}{\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k})^{2}.

This further implies that

JS(Fk𝒜||Fk𝒪)≤12(e2​ξ−1)TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮).\displaystyle\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k})}\leq\frac{1}{2}(e^{2\xi}-1){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}).

Notice that the square root of the Jensen-Shannon divergence satisfies the triangle inequality. Then we have that

JS(Fk𝒪||Fkℬ)−JS(Fk𝒜||Fkℬ)≤JS(Fk𝒜||Fk𝒪)≤12(e2​ξ−1)TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮).\displaystyle\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})}-\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})}\leq\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k})}\leq\frac{1}{2}(e^{2\xi}-1){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}).

Therefore, we have

JS(Fk𝒪||Fkℬ)\displaystyle\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{O}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})} ≤JS(Fk𝒜||Fkℬ)+12(e2​ξ−1)TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮)\displaystyle\leq\sqrt{{\text{JS}}(F^{\mathcal{A}}_{k}||F^{\mathcal{B}}_{k})}+\frac{1}{2}(e^{2\xi}-1){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k})
=ϵp,k+12(e2​ξ−1)TV(Pk𝒪||Pk𝒮).\displaystyle=\epsilon_{p,k}+\frac{1}{2}(e^{2\xi}-1){\text{TV}}(P_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}||P^{\mathcal{S}}_{k}).

∎

Appendix B Bayesian Inference Attack In SFL

It was shown that semi-honest adversaries can recover the private training images with pixel-level accuracy from unprotected gradients of learned models. We assume that an adversary aims to recover the kt​hsubscript𝑘𝑡ℎk_{th} client’s private variable Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} from exposed variable Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}, which is the output of applying certain protection mechanisms on model information i.e. Wk𝒮=M​(Wk𝒪)superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮𝑀superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}=M(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}), where M𝑀M is a protection mechanism.

In this section, we formulate three privacy leakage attacks of SFL including gradient-inverse attack (Zhu and Han, 2020; Geiping et al., 2020; Zhao et al., 2020a; Yin et al., 2021), model inversion attack (Fredrikson et al., 2015; He et al., 2019) and brute-force attack (especially for encryption) from the Bayesian Inference perspective. Such a Bayesian Inference Attack mechanism is defined as follows:

Definition B.0 (Bayesian Inference Attack).

A Bayesian Inference Attack111111The Bayesian inference framework has long been applied to the image restoration problem as early as in 1960s (Dempster, 1968; Geman and Geman, 1984b; Box and Tiao, 2011). is an optimization process that aims to infer the private variable Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} in order to best fit the exposed information Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} i.e.,

(33) d∗=argmaxdlog⁡(fSk|Wk𝒮​(d|w))=argmaxdlog⁡(fWk𝒮|Sk​(w|d)​fDk​(d)fWk𝒮​(w))=argmaxd[log⁡fWk𝒮|Sk​(w|d)+log⁡fDk​(d)],=argmaxd[L1​(d,Wk𝒮)+L2​(d)],\begin{split}d^{*}&=\operatorname*{argmax}\limits_{d}\log\left(f_{S_{k}|W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}}(d|w)\right)\\ &=\operatorname*{argmax}\limits_{d}\log\left(\frac{f_{W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}|S_{k}}(w|d)f_{D_{k}}(d)}{f_{W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}}(w)}\right)\\ &=\operatorname*{argmax}\limits_{d}[\log f_{W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}|S_{k}}(w|d)+\log f_{D_{k}}(d)],\\ &=\operatorname*{argmax}\limits_{d}[L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}})+L_{2}(d)],\end{split}

where L1​(d,Wk𝒮)=log⁡fWk𝒮|Sk​(w|d)subscript𝐿1𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮subscript𝑓conditionalsuperscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮subscript𝑆𝑘conditional𝑤𝑑L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}})=\log f_{W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}|S_{k}}(w|d) and L2​(d)=log⁡fDk​(d)subscript𝐿2𝑑subscript𝑓subscript𝐷𝑘𝑑L_{2}(d)=\log f_{D_{k}}(d).

There are three types of Bayesian Inference attack as follows:

B.1. Gradient Inversion Attack

In the SFL, private model updates (gradients) and model 121212when updating model, the server could obtain the model gradients by calculating the difference between two uploaded models needed to be uploaded to the server, which may be taken use to reconstruct the input data of clients by semi-honest adversaries. In this setting, gradient-inverse attack is proposed in (Zhu and Han, 2020) to infer the private data Dksubscript𝐷𝑘D_{k} from the model gradients (exposed information Wk𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}} here is model gradients G𝐺G). The form of L1​(d,Wk𝒮)subscript𝐿1𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}) is:

(34) L1​(d,Wk𝒮)=L1​(d,G)=C−‖∇W​(d)−G‖2,subscript𝐿1𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮subscript𝐿1𝑑𝐺𝐶superscriptnorm∇𝑊𝑑𝐺2L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}})=L_{1}(d,G)=C-\|\nabla W(d)-G\|^{2},

in which ∇W​(d)∇𝑊𝑑\nabla W(d) is the gradient of training loss w.r.t. model parameters for the estimated data d𝑑d, and G𝐺G is the observed gradients of model parameters.

B.1.1. Influence of prior in gradient inversion attack

Moreover, the prior L2​(d)=log⁡fDk​(d)subscript𝐿2𝑑subscript𝑓subscript𝐷𝑘𝑑L_{2}(d)=\log f_{D_{k}}(d) is an important factor for Bayesian Inference attack, a series of work was developed to use different prior in gradient inversion attack.

  • •

    No prior: Zhu et al. (Zhu and Han, 2020) proposed the gradient inversion attack in which reconstructed private data is randomly initialized.

  • •

    Smoothness prior: Geiping et al. (Geiping et al., 2020) improved the attack with the smoothness of data (such as image). Specifically, they viewed the TV loss of the data as the smoothness: L2​(d)=TV​(d)subscript𝐿2𝑑TV𝑑L_{2}(d)={\text{TV}}(d).

  • •

    Label prior: Zhao et. al (Zhao et al., 2020a) developed the prior with the label information of the data, that is, L2​(d)=Label​(d)subscript𝐿2𝑑Label𝑑L_{2}(d)=\text{Label}(d).

  • •

    Group consistency prior: Besides smoothness and label of data, Yin et al. (Yin et al., 2021) applied group consistency of estimated data to the training process of Gradient inversion attack, where L2​(d)=Group​(d)subscript𝐿2𝑑Group𝑑L_{2}(d)=\text{Group}(d).

Moreover, the results of (Zhu and Han, 2020; Geiping et al., 2020; Zhao et al., 2020a; Yin et al., 2021) demonstrate that different prior would cause a different type of privacy leakage. Stronger prior of private data let the adversaries attack the private data of clients more effectively. For example, the attack method proposed by (Yin et al., 2021) combined three priors: smoothness, label, and group consistency into gradient inversion attack. It is shown that their attack performs best in images with large batch size compared to other gradient inversion methods.

B.2. Model Inversion Attack

In some cases of SFL, such as split learning (Gupta and Raskar, 2018), or vertical federated learning (Yang et al., 2019a), the model outputs O𝑂O may be leaked. A new reconstruction attack are proposed according to the exposed model outputs O𝑂O in (Fredrikson et al., 2015; He et al., 2019), called model inversion attack with the following L1​(d,Wk𝒮=O)subscript𝐿1𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮𝑂L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}=O) loss function:

(35) L1(d,Wk𝒮)=L1(d,O)=C−||O^(d)−O)||2,{L}_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}})={L}_{1}(d,O)=C-||\hat{O}(d)-O)||^{2},

in which O^​(d)^𝑂𝑑\hat{O}(d) is the output of the training model with respect to the data d𝑑d and O𝑂O is the observed output of models for the private data.

B.3. Brute-force Attack for Encryption

In the cryptosystem, the attack problem is formulated to restore private Key given chosen plaintext and ciphertext (CPA). The brute-force method in a cryptosystem is to try all possible private keys until the chosen plaintext matches plaintext. Similarly, this formulation could also be written as a Bayesian inference attack with L1​(d,Wk𝒮)subscript𝐿1𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}) as:

L1(d,Wk𝒮)=L1(d,(Wk𝒪,Enc(Wk𝒪)))={1,decrypt​(d,Enc​(Wk𝒪))=Wk𝒪0,decrypt​(d,Enc​(Wk𝒪))≠Wk𝒪L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}})=L_{1}(d,(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}},\text{Enc}(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}})))=\left\{\begin{aligned} 1,\quad\text{decrypt}(d,\text{Enc}(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}))=W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}\\ 0,\quad\text{decrypt}(d,\text{Enc}(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}))\neq W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}\\ \end{aligned}\right.

where d𝑑d is the estimation of private key, Wk𝒮=(Wk𝒪,Enc​(Wk𝒪))superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪Encsuperscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}=(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}},\text{Enc}(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}})) is pair of plaintext model information Wk𝒪superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}} and ciphertext Enc​(Wk𝒪)Encsuperscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒪\text{Enc}(W_{k}^{\mathcal{O}}).

B.4. Time complexity of Bayesian Inference Attack

For Gradient inversion and model inversion attack, it could be solved by the optimization loss as :

(36) maxd⁡L​(d)=maxd⁡[L1​(d,Wk𝒮)+L2​(d)]=maxd⁡[‖J​(d)−wk𝒮‖2+L2​(d)],subscript𝑑𝐿𝑑subscript𝑑subscript𝐿1𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑊𝑘𝒮subscript𝐿2𝑑subscript𝑑superscriptnorm𝐽𝑑superscriptsubscript𝑤𝑘𝒮2subscript𝐿2𝑑\max\limits_{d}L(d)=\max\limits_{d}[L_{1}(d,W_{k}^{\mathcal{S}})+L_{2}(d)]=\max\limits_{d}[||J(d)-w_{k}^{\mathcal{S}}||^{2}+L_{2}(d)],

where J𝐽J represents the mapping from data to model gradients in gradient inversion attack, and the mapping from data to model outputs in model inversion attack.

Proposition B.1.

The time complexity to solve Eq. (36) is polynomial, if any of the following conditions are satisfied:

  • •

    L𝐿L is convex and smooth (moreover, the convergence rate is O​(1t)𝑂1𝑡O(\frac{1}{t})).

  • •

    L𝐿L is convex but non-smooth, and L𝐿L is Lipschitz continuous (moreover, the convergence rate is O​(1t)𝑂1𝑡O(\frac{1}{\sqrt{t}})).

  • •

    L𝐿L is non-convex and L𝐿L-Smooth (moreover, the convergence rate is O​(1t2)𝑂1superscript𝑡2O(\frac{1}{t^{2}})).

Remark: Proposition B.1 demonstrates three conditions of L𝐿L that the optimization problem Eq. (36) is polynomial time. For the analysis of this proposition please refer to (Boyd et al., 2004).
For Bayesian inference methods of encryption, Gentry et al. (Gentry et al., 2013) proposed a simple fully homomorphic encryption (FHE) scheme (approximate eigenvector method) based on the learning with errors (LWE) problem (Regev, 2009). They prove the security of proposed scheme on G​a​p​S​V​Pγ𝐺𝑎𝑝𝑆𝑉subscript𝑃𝛾GapSVP_{\gamma} via a classical reduction from LWE (Brakerski et al., 2013; Brakerski, 2012; Peikert, 2009). The best algorithms (Schnorr, 1987; Micciancio and Voulgaris, 2013) for G​a​p​S​V​Pγ𝐺𝑎𝑝𝑆𝑉subscript𝑃𝛾GapSVP_{\gamma} requires at least 2Ω​(nd/l​o​g​γ)superscript2Ωsubscript𝑛𝑑𝑙𝑜𝑔𝛾2^{\Omega(n_{d}/log\gamma)} time. The approximate eigenvector method reduces from γ=ndO​(log⁡(nd))𝛾superscriptsubscript𝑛𝑑𝑂subscript𝑛𝑑\gamma=n_{d}^{O(\log(n_{d}))}, for which the best known algorithms run in time 2Ω​(nd)superscript2Ωsubscript𝑛𝑑2^{\Omega(n_{d})}. Paillier is a probabilistic asymmetric algorithm for public key cryptography based on decisional composite residuosity assumption (Paillier, 1999). Since it has additive homomorphic property, paillier could be applied into Fedaverage (Zhang et al., 2019; Aono et al., 2017; Truex et al., 2019; Cheng et al., 2021) in FL, which only needs addition operations. As far as we know, the most efficient algorithm against paillier encryption is based on factoring of the a large number (Paillier, 1999). That is also the best known attack against RSA encryption(Rivest et al., 1978). One of the widely-known efficient algorithms for factoring the large number is general number field sieve (GNFS) (Buhler et al., 1993), the time complexity of which is sub-exponential (exp⁡((6493+o​(1))​(ln⁡n)13​(ln⁡ln⁡n)23)3649𝑜1superscript𝑛13superscript𝑛23\exp((\sqrt[3]{\frac{64}{9}}+o(1))(\ln n)^{\frac{1}{3}}(\ln\ln n)^{\frac{2}{3}})).
